CatDescriptText: Cutline of image published in Pittsburgh Courier newspaper, September 10, 1960, pg. 9 reads: "Empty Lot Was Negro Home - Arrow points to empty lot at 552 Sedddon Ave., where the home of elderly Mrs. James Underwood, a great-grandmother, was razed in the past year after she and her family had vacated the structure. In August, the second Negro home on the same street, a house owned by Mrs. Loretta Hawkins, 142 Watkins Ave., Wilmerding, also was razed, while Mrs. Hawkins was vainly trying to get a building permit to make repairs, and while she was busy arranging papers for the sale of the house and lot to a Negro buyer. - Harris Photo."
TitMainTitle: Car parked in front of empty lot between stone and brick houses with porches, where home of Mrs. James Underwood was razed, 552 Seddon Avenue, North Braddock
